Mortier had to reorganize the French Army in the light of the war in the east and, more importantly, the defeat of the Wehrmacht in the Battle of Stalingrad. This was a turning point in the history of the French Army, as it was the first time that the Luftwaffe had been defeated on the Eastern Front. The reorganization took place in two phases: the first phase was an attempt to re-equip the French Army with the equipment it had lost in the summer of 1941, while the second phase was the preparation of a new offensive, codenamed Barbarossa (Black Sea). During the first phase, the French Army suffered heavy losses, especially in the Artois and Alsace-Lorraine Provinces. In the second phase, the German counterattacking was too strong and the French Army was forced to withdraw to the Ardennes (see Battle of the Bulge). After the Second World War, the remnants of the French Army were amalgamated into the newly formed Army Group Générale de la République (ARGORSA) and reorganized into the Fifth Army (see Operation STORM).

